04264nam a22006255i 9780292760981DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927609817 a10.7560/7609742doi  a(DE-B1597)588366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43 6552231 aGordon, Richard A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCinema, Slavery, and Brazilian Nationalism /cRichard A. Gordon. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Influencing Understandings of Brazilianness in O Aleijadinho: Paixão, glória e suplício (2000) -- tChapter Two. Modeling National Identity on Religious Identity in Cafundó (2005) -- tChapter Three. Multiple, Provisional, National Identity Models in Quilombo (1984) -- tChapter Four. Alternative Understandings of the National Community in Chico Rei (1985) -- tChapter Five. Flirting with Viewers and Precariously Rethinking Brazilianness in Xica da Silva (1976) -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA unique contribution to film studies, Richard Gordon’s Cinema, Slavery, and Brazilian Nationalism is the first full-length book on Brazilian films about slavery. By studying Brazilian films released between 1976 and 2005, Gordon examines how the films both define the national community and influence viewer understandings of Brazilianness. Though the films he examines span decades, they all communicate their revised version of Brazilian national identity through a cinematic strategy with a dual aim: to upset ingrained ways of thinking about Brazil and to persuade those who watch the films to accept a new way of understanding their national community. By examining patterns in this heterogeneous group of films, Gordon proposes a new way of delineating how these films attempt to communicate with and change the minds of audience members. Gordon outlines five key aspects that each film incorporates, which describe their shared formula for and role in constructing social identity. These elements include the ways in which the films attempt to create links between the past and the viewers’ present and their methods of encouraging viewers to identify with their protagonists, who are often cast as a prototype for the nation. By aligning themselves with this figure, viewers arrive at a definition of their national identity that, while Afrocentric, also promotes racial and ethnic inclusiveness. Gordon’s innovative analysis transcends the context of his work, and his conclusions can be applied to questions of national identity and film across cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszBrazil. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aNationalism in motion pictures. 0aSlavery in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292760981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292760981/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK